                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d25">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/10107: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Geneva</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bucknell</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-09-16T22:00:00+01:00"
                            >September 16, 1937—10 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received September 16—6:06 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>304. Consulate’s 302, September 16, 5 p.m., paragraph 4. Council in private
                    session this afternoon acted as forecast. Koo made reservation that if proposal
                    to convoke Advisory Committee and refer appeal to it was agreed to, that Council
                    remained seized of the Chinese appeal itself and that he further reserved the
                    right to ask Council to act in accordance with procedure of three articles cited
                    in Chinese appeal if and when circumstances required it.</p>
                <p>Koo informed me that the Advisory Committee will probably hold its first meeting
                    either Monday<note n="32" xml:id="d25fn32">September 20.</note> or Tuesday
                    next.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bucknell</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
